{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"72076d0e-3444-4841-b36c-62ca07a2cc41","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's the difference:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what you need to bring workloads (like `maui`) in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — **Reinstalls** the same versions already recorded. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but won't pull newer, SDK-compatible versions.\n\n**TL;DR:** `repair` fixes broken installs; `update` gets versions that match your new SDK. Since your SDK changed, `update` is the right call:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails afterward, try a clean + rebuild (`dotnet clean && dotnet build`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b9850272-0ee3-42ae-91b3-562553e19b70","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":260,"requestId":"0455:B86C3:A8F2E6:C14B3D:6A027927"},"id":"78bc28cf-da1b-4baa-ab26-7fbfdf836185","timestamp":"2026-05-12T00:49:51.824Z","parentId":"48d43c4a-31aa-428a-86a9-7f5911e0ab41"}
